Astrea of the Stars 09-Aug-21 10:16 PM
Charlie, huh? Certainly an odd name... but it does mean 'free man'. To be free is to be human, one could argue - it means freedom to do whatever you please, without worry of anything else getting in the way. Thus, the symbol that's on the doors and the walls here is a star. There's also a label on the door that says 'CHARLIE ROOM'. Speaking of which: you can tell there's a lock on the door, but if you're coming in here before the room is fully claimed, it'll allow you in without complain. After the room has been fully claimed, the door will open only if it senses that one of the 4 members of the room are within 5 feet of it from the outside. They don't seem particularly homely - all of the walls and ceilings are made out of a near-black metal, though the lighting in this room is decent enough. There are two sets of bunk beds in each room - enough to hold four people. If you're coming in here for the first time, you can claim any of the beds that hasn't been claimed yet. The beds themselves are incredibly well made - they feel like pure bliss. The mattress feels just right to the touch and immediately adjusts to whoever is laying on it, the covers and blankets feel soft, and the pillows themselves automatically morph into the shape that'll work for you, somehow. Impressive. There are also four cabinets here - they are, oddly enough, wooden, somewhat sticking out from the rest of the place. The cabinets have the name of the person who presumably owns the cabinets, notebook paper and a pencil on top of them, and clothes of whoever owns it. This all is automatically done as the person 'registers' by walking through the door. There's also a trash can to the side of them, emptied out each day.
There are two bathrooms to the side. The sink is... a sink, though you notice it has all of the skin, hair, and dental care that you could ever ask for. The toilet is one of the Japanese deluxe toilets that have a variety of features that you have no idea what they do - they can sing to you, clean you up (though there is also toilet paper here), heat your.. bottom, etc. Plenty of towels also line the bathroom, and they seem to be refreshed every day. There's a place to throw your dirty clothes, but of course, there's also the shower, which, while a standing shower, automatically adjusts to the temperature you like and has plenty of hair care and shower products. There's a fancy tub near the shower with much of the same equipment (except there is some special tub equipment, too, so yes, you can have a bubble bath), so that's neat.
